  "response": "The **highest level of C** refers to the **Level of Certification (LOC)** assigned to a **C Package** in the context of **DO-178C**, the software standard for airborne systems. DO- **Level C** is the **middle level of certification** for software, with five levels (A to E) defined based on the **criticality of the software** to aircraft safety.\n\n### DO-178C Certification Levels:\n1. **Level A** (Most Critical): Software whose anomalous behavior could cause or contribute to a catastrophic failure of the aircraft.\n2. **Level B**: Software whose anomalous behavior could cause or contribute to a hazardous failure condition.\n3. **Level C**: Software whose anomalous behavior could cause or contribute to a major failure condition.\n4. **Level D**: Software whose anomalous behavior could cause or contribute to a minor failure condition.\n5. **Level E** (Least Critical): Software whose anomalous behavior has no safety impact.\n\nThus, there is no \"higher level\" than **Level C**; it is already a well-defined level in DO-178C. However, Levels A and B are more critical and stringent than Level C.",
